In answer to the first query, the committee will please to know, that about the year 1740, I heard John Fleming, a taylor, who in the manner of the country, worked with his journeyrnen at my father’s house, repeat, in a kind of ehiming measure, heroic strains relating to an arrival or landing of an host and a subsequent battle, with a single combat of two chiefs. This I took down in writing, and kept for some time3 but was not in possession of when Mr Maepherson’s publications appeared. I had no doubt,

however, in recognizing the same passage in the arrival of Swaran, and the single combat with Cuchullin, in Mac- 'pherson’s translation of F ingal. r The few words [can recal, are, lst, in relation to the hosts engaged ε “ Iomma colan, iornma skia, iomma tria, is lurigh gharibh. And in relation to the chiefs who grappled, and in whose struggle- Bha cloghin agus talamh trom moscle fo bhonn an cos. ’ ⁴ The Committee will be so good as excuse my spelling, and guess at the words as they best can.
